### Success notifications

Use a green success notification banner to alert the user that the action they performed was successful. Success notifications are automatically focused after a page loads.

{{ example({group: "components", item: "notification-banner", example: "success", html: true, open: true, size: "s"}) }}

Only use a success notification when it’s not obvious from the context that the user’s action was successful.

### Error notifications

Use a red error notification banner to alert the user that the action they performed (such as filling out a form) was not successful. Error notifications are automatically focused after a page loads.

{{ example({group: "components", item: "notification-banner", example: "error", html: true, open: true, size: "s"}) }}

Find out how to use error notification banners to help users [Recover from validation errors](/patterns/validation/).

### Accessibility

Never rely on the colour of the notification alone to communicate information to the user - the content and context of the notification must be sufficient for this.

Standard blue notifications have `role="region"`  and `aria-label="notice"` attributes added to them so that they are correctly handled by assistive technologies.

Success and error notifications have `role="alert"` , `tab-index=-1`  and `data-module="initial-focus"` attributes applied. This makes sure that keyboard focus is shifted to them when they first appear, so that screen-reader users are immediately made aware of them.

### Removing notification banners

Notification banners should persist for as long as the information they contain is relevant.

If a notification banner is no longer relevant you should remove it when the user next performs a meaningful action, such as leaving or refreshing the page.

Do not remove a notification banner before the user has moved on to the next action, as they may not have had time to read it.

### Positioning notification banners

Position notification banners immediately before the page heading. This gives them visual prominence when the page loads, without breaking up the flow of the document. 

Avoid showing multiple notification banners of the same type on the same page. Instead, combine them into a single banner, like this:

{{ example({group: "components", item: "notification-banner", example: "error-multiple", html: true, open: true, size: "s"}) }}

If you have a persistent status message, you could temporarily replace it with an alert and then reinstate the status message after a page refresh or by dismissing the alert.

If you still need to show multiple notification banners then put an alert before a standard banner.

Do not show error alerts and success alerts at the same time. Avoid partial successes and only show success when there are no errors.

## Research on this component

More research is needed to understand whether:

* it's sometimes helpful to allow users to dismiss notifications, and the best way to let them do this
* to use alert notifications for actions with a delayed outcome - such as the result of an overnight batch process
* users sometimes miss important information in notification banners
